The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, gave remarks at a naturalization ceremony where 16 new Americans were welcomed into the country. He thanked Secretary Elaine Chao and other public servants for their work and congratulated the new citizens. Pence spoke about the importance of immigration and the contributions that immigrants make to the nation. He also mentioned the challenges currently facing the country, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, but expressed confidence in the resilience and strength of the American people. Pence encouraged the new citizens to embrace their roles in making a stronger and more prosperous America and to give back to their communities. He shared his own family's immigration story and emphasized the opportunities and freedoms that the United States offers. Pence ended his remarks by congratulating the new citizens and urging them to continue dreaming big in their new home.